<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="151" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,654,1327]" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1158,1183]" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from the word “striate”, refers to form of the sculpture of ventral process of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="151" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,654,1327]" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1230,1255]" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">Remarks.</emphasis>
The species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kuoh &amp; Hu" authorityName="Kuoh &amp; Hu" authorityYear="1992" box="[665,919,1230,1255]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Parafagocyba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="binaria">
<emphasis box="[665,776,1230,1254]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">P. binaria</emphasis>
Kuoh &amp; Hu
</taxonomicName>
in the form of the aedeagus, but differs in its dorsal coloration, subgenital plate with two macrosetae near base, and the more basal location of the sculptures on the ventral process of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
